04482nam a22006975i 9780226401607DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264016077 a10.7208/97802264016072doi  a(DE-B1597)524907  a(OCoLC)961271885  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aML1733.2b.W55 2017 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a782.1090322231 aWilbourne, Emily, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSeventeenth-Century Opera and the Sound of the Commedia dell'Arte /cEmily Wilbourne. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b5 halftones, 37 line drawings,  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote to the Reader -- tIntroduction. "The Tragedies and Comedies Recited by the Zanni" -- tChapter one. The Commedia dell'Arte as Theater -- tChapter two. "Ma meglio di tutti Arianna comediante" -- tChapter three. The Serious Elements of Early Comic Opera -- tChapter four. Penelope and Poppea as Stock Figures of the Commedia dell'Arte -- tConclusion. Seventeenth- Century Opera and the Sound of the Commedia dell'Arte -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this book, Emily Wilbourne boldly traces the roots of early opera back to the sounds of the commedia dell'arte. Along the way, she forges a new history of Italian opera, from the court pieces of the early seventeenth century to the public stages of Venice more than fifty years later. Wilbourne considers a series of case studies structured around the most important and widely explored operas of the period: Monteverdi's lost L'Arianna, as well as his Il Ritorno d'Ulisse and L'incoronazione di Poppea; Mazzochi and Marazzoli's L'Egisto, ovvero Chi soffre speri; and Cavalli's L'Ormindo and L'Artemisia. As she demonstrates, the sound-in-performance aspect of commedia dell'arte theater-specifically, the use of dialect and verbal play-produced an audience that was accustomed to listening to sonic content rather than simply the literal meaning of spoken words. This, Wilbourne suggests, shaped the musical vocabularies of early opera and facilitated a musicalization of Italian theater. Highlighting productive ties between the two worlds, from the audiences and venues to the actors and singers, this work brilliantly shows how the sound of commedia performance ultimately underwrote the success of opera as a genre.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCommedia dell'artexCharacters. 0aCommedia dell'artexHistory and criticism. 0aCommedia dell'artexInfluence. 0aOperazItalyy17th century. 4aClaudio Monteverdi. 4aFrancesco Cavalli. 4aVirginia Andreini. 4aaria. 4acommedia dell'arte. 4alament. 4alistening. 4aopera. 4arecitative. 4asound. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226401607423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226401607.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles